title: The Witcher Season 2 Episode 4 - Spoilers

title: AITA for telling my husband I don't want to have kids?
self_text: My husband and I have been together for 5 years now, married for 3. We both come from big families with lots of cousins and siblings so we grew up around a lot of children. When we started dating he told me he wanted at least 2 kids but I said that wasn’t something I was interested in. He accepted it and said as long as we were happy then he didn’t care if we had any or not. I never thought anything of it because we’d talked about it many times over the past 5 years and he always seemed okay with it.  Last week out of nowhere he brought up having kids again. He said his mother asked him when he was going to give her grandchildren and he felt bad that she would be sad if we didn’t have them. I reminded him that we talked about this already and I still don’t want kids. He got upset and accused me of changing my mind even though I haven’t. He said that if I really loved him then I’d change my mind for him and our family. I told him that love doesn’t mean changing yourself for someone else and he needs to accept me for who I am. He stormed off and hasn’t spoken to me since.  I feel like I’m being put in an impossible situation. I don’t want kids and I don’t think anyone should be forced into becoming a parent. But I also don’t want to lose my marriage.   AITA?

title: UCLA student found dead in dorm room
self_text: A UCLA student was found dead in his dorm room early Sunday morning, university officials said. The student has been identified as Brandon Chang, a 20-year-old sophomore from San Ramon.  Police are investigating the cause of death, but have not released any further information.  "We are deeply saddened by the loss of our student," UCLA Chancellor Gene Block said in a statement. "Our thoughts and prayers are with his family and friends."  Chang was majoring in computer science and engineering. He was a member of the Alpha Phi Omega service fraternity and the Bruin Robotics Club.   The incident comes just days after another UCLA student died in an apparent suicide.  Anyone who is struggling with mental health issues can reach out for help by calling the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at 988 or texting HOME to 741741.  More on this story here: https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2023-05-29/ucla-student-found-dead-dorm-room

title: 1967 - 1972 Chevelle, Malibu and Monte Carlo Engine Identification
self_text: I've got a bunch of numbers from my engine (cast number, date code, VIN derivative) but I can't seem to figure out what it is. I'm looking for an early to mid-size V8. The cast number is 3955557, the date code is A2072, and the VIN derivative is B247.   I have been doing some research on these numbers and have found that they are all related to Chevrolet engines made in Tonawanda, New York between 1967 and 1972.  However, the exact details of these codes are difficult to find.   Here is what I've learned so far:   Cast Number: This number identifies the core design of the engine block. It doesn't tell you much about the specific year or model. Date Code: This code tells you when the engine block was cast. In this case, "A" means January and "20" means the 20th day of the month. So the block was cast on January 20th, 1972.  VIN Derivative: This is where things get tricky. The VIN derivative is supposed to identify the original vehicle the engine came from. However, there are several different interpretations of what each digit means.  The most common interpretation is as follows:   B = 1967   2 = Mid-Size Car   4 = V8 Engine   7 = Power Steering   So based on this interpretation, your engine is from a 1967 mid-size car with a V8 engine and power steering.  However, other sources say that the VIN derivative also includes information about the transmission type and rear axle ratio.  If we take those into account, then your engine could be from a 1967 mid-size car with a V8 engine, automatic transmission and 3.08 rear axle ratio. title: UCLA vs USC Men's Basketball - Game Preview and Discussion!
self_text:
The #17 Bruins (24-6, 13-5) head to the Galen Center for a showdown against the #20 Trojans (25-6, 13-5). This is the first of two meetings between these Pac-12 rivals in March.   UCLA leads the series all-time 149-118, but USC has won three of the last four.  The winner will be in position to win the Pac-12 regular season title outright with a victory next week at home against Arizona and on the road against ASU.  A loss could send them into a tie for the lead with Oregon or even drop them down into the third seed for the conference tournament.  

**Game Details:**
* **Date/Time:** Saturday, March 4, 2023 @ 2:30 PM PST
* **Location:** Galen Center, Los Angeles, CA
* **TV:** CBS
* **Radio:** AM 570 KLAC
* **Livestream:** [https://www.espn.com/watch/player/_/id/38842693](https://www.espn.com/watch/player/_/id/38842693)

**UCLA Starting Lineup (as of February 28th):**
1. Jaylen Clark
2. Tyger Campbell
3. Jaime Jaquez Jr.
4. Amari Bailey
5. Adem Bona

**USC Starting Lineup (as of February 28th):**
1. Boogie Ellis
2. Tre White
3. Kobe Johnson
4. Reese Dixon-Waters
5. Drew Peterson

**Key Matchups to Watch:**
* **Jaime Jaquez Jr. vs. Drew Peterson:** Both are all-around players who can score, rebound, and defend. Expect a lot of physicality in their battles.
* **Adem Bona vs. Reese Dixon-Waters:** Two big men who bring energy and athleticism to the paint. Their performances will be crucial for controlling the boards.
* **Boogie Ellis vs. Jaylen Clark:** Two high level perimeter defenders that play off ball.

**What do you think will happen? What keys will determine the outcome? Let’s discuss!**

title: What's the worst thing you ever did to get a good grade?
self_text: I was in high school and had a math test on Friday that would determine if I passed or failed, so my friend gave me an answer key she got from her brother who took it last year.  I went home after class Thursday night and made a copy of the answers on a piece of paper, then hid it under my pencil case.  The next day during the test, when I wasn't looking, he looked at my desk and saw the sheet.  He said "oh wow, you are really doing everything you can to pass" and laughed.   So I threw it away, but I ended up failing anyway.
